Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation, which is measured in the eurozone, is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was registered, as the EU's Statistical Office reports in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are expected to be of just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate. In their discretion, the rate cut would favour rising commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is keen to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least narrowly, at the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a quandary: inflation must be "denounced" in order to rule out the need for action later.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in November in Germany reached a twelve-year record high; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in food and energy prices is responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
MATIF wheat quotations rose 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also hit a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in inflation in cooking oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the coming 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate, but estimate the average annual rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
