In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals, which were due to an improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overloading of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to curbing the infections, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
There was already a similar infection here at the beginning of the year.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Important surgery has not yet been performed because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
To 10. December of this year, infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System in 1094, according to senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were certainly registered in the hospitals, but the dark number is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without it causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, said Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," according to Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples too rare
The majority of infections in hospitals caused by MRSA would be preventable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and retirement homes, the hospitals should examine the admitted patients and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not so frequently practiced in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation on the part of the state health insurance.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has made strict recommendations on the use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and disease patterns in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary so that resistance to the agent cannot form, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among the outpatients or primary care patients, microbiological sampling is even less common, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Savings are made on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to the other by nursing staff.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also considerable deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds barely lined up, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz continues to note, unfortunately, it even happens in the financially less well-placed hospitals that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are adhered to, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting to grips with MRSA infections causes huge costs to health insurance companies, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment was recorded in the government programme.
After initial signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
