Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed three loan agreements worth EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday. The money will go to education, transport and environmental protection infrastructure and the energy industry.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental protection projects, which are implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement for 100 million has already been signed earlier, the current agreement is about the use of the €200 million in love.
The amount of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary and the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly flow into research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
The meeting also discussed the subway line 4.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of metro funding with the EU, the original treaty and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest is EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, commission-free.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is attentive to the Balkan state, which was rarely mentioned before.
What, where, and who buys on the still cheapest market in the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis by the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after patch for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and seafront homes.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, on the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russe is seeing more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, and thus attracting tourists in the other two seasons in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
Forefronting investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who acquire real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle, either buy revitalized properties by 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are very important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group make up business people who invest with the goal of a medium- to long-term increase in value.
Real estate in the capital, however, is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been a price increase of 21 percent annually.
The inflation in property prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings come to an end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol.
A fierce debate is currently underway between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether developed countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement has also been reached on support for developing countries.
The Adaptation Fund, which is subject to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be managed by a 16-member Council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be read in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s aspiration to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 levels), regardless of whether or not the "after 2012 agreement" would be successfully achieved. The Union would even be willing to advocate for a 30 percent reduction, provided that other major industrialized countries in the world, or Developing countries are also prepared to fulfil their commitments to the best of their ability and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the states that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU with its 15 member states at the time had already committed to a minus of 8%.
The requirement for Hungary is a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be ready within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the UN’s International Nobel Peace Prize-winning Scientific Climate Change Committee, in its latest report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and increasing the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for increasing popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been loading videos about against the Taliban-led operations on the net since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The footage, shot with miniature cameras attached to helmets, is checked at the air base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are put on the internet.
Political message unavoidable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The UK Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeepers (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual targets of foreign operations.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, such propaganda published in this way is almost free of charge compared to conventional television advertisements, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the right to exist of the military measures adopted by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
However, the army must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored recordings, also make it to the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of the theatres of war in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, numerous videos shot in action have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre" for themselves.
The Americans, meanwhile, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-sacre simulation.
