Political Capital: Hungarian Guard raises state risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "risk warning report" states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk poses the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic confrontations in the short term."
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at the provocation of such a dispute, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposite".
It is assumed that this would exacerbate the problem, make sensible dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also thinks that the activities of the Hungarian Guard have, not least thanks to the enormous attention on the part of the domestic and foreign media, "significantly damage the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of trust in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since the autumn of 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the upswing, so that since the summer of 2007 several organizations that call themselves "national self-defense" have been founded.
"These groups have in common that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly bragging about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defensive tasks (disaster protection, national defense, order guard), citing the unfitness of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: This is all done according to the method which tries to camouflage various political aspirations based on the political and party discontent of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of association therefore serve not only to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration in court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighboring states, so some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighboring countries see in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of his own anti-Hungary policy.
This all has implications for the region's political stability" - it said.
