Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redisposing the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year will give us fewer such days.
In the EU and America, too, something else is meant by "holiday."
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and days off from work.
Work-free days are mostly church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
We also celebrate New Year’s Day, for example: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days – the latter alone so that the New Year’s Eve celebraters can rest.
Throughout the year, we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are the 15th. March commemorating the revolution of 1848, and the 23. October, the day of the 1956 Revolution.
On the 20. August will be the founding of the state, on the 1. May the work celebrated, on the 1. and 2. We remember our dead in November.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proven itself in those cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
However, the price of the extended weekends is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is ultimately to be processed, has been set out for many years by the Minister of Labour in its own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, to public employees and civil servants alike.
Excluded are only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays.
This year, the working order is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from the 24. December, life in this country remains a formal standing still, as most take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the specially cancelled holiday.
Next year, more holidays will fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so that there will be fewer reschedulings in the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work so that people can stay home for four days at a time.
Saturday, the 26th April will be a working day so that Friday, 2. May can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling hangs with the holiday on the 23. October together: On Saturday, the 18th October will be Friday, 24. Have to work October in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely marked by the holidays, after from the 24. December everything lies and stops, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
