Cuba - most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it really is an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, that will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is calm like a pond.
Palm trees and all-inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this to an abundant extent.
Only on one island, however, you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a warehouse or transit camp of treasures that the Spanish had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was created at the very end of the 20th. century.
One of the heads of the American Mafia, Lucky Luciano, was built, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during Prohibition) was gladly seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, over the wide boulevards drove cars, which were among the cult symbols of the 1950s of the past century.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional, you can mix cocktails as you wish.
And the cult cars of the 1950s are still driving around Havana today, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and moist air.
May Havana, especially its oldest part, have come down considerably, nowhere can you find so many wonderful colonial sights in the vicinity as right now.
Other places are being cleaned out right now, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have been built not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a quirk that is unique in the world and attracts railroad lovers in particular.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-powered narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives there, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
The most significant places do not leave out the majority of Cuba's visitors.
So you no longer have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
It remains to be mentioned that in the already mentioned Hemingway estate there is a museum, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, through which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
Perhaps it also seems interesting to some people that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Fame and fortune brought her the trade in slaves and sugar.
The wealth embodied itself in the pretty beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there in the fifties of the last century that would have connected the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation helped make it go unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth to see interesting places in the area, such as the beach Playa Ancón or the "Valley of the Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la Música, which enlivens after the darkness, and where the music is not silent until the morning.
Baracoa
Some people describe this town in the very east of Cuba as the most beautiful of the island.
To be sure, this view is also influenced by the way to it.
Both roads that lead from Guantánamo must overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is barely touched by human intervention.
UNESCO included this Eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage directory thanks to the unspoiled nature there.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can show the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill, where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, several table mountains can be seen, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra Mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this could be written many pages.
But, as they say, look better with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
Too few soldiers and the lack of necessary equipment, according to the United States, influences the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
NATO should, according to Defense Minister Robert Gates, draft a concrete plan for the next few years.
The mission in Afghanistan did not proceed according to their ideas, the representatives of the countries that have stationed units in the south of the country in Edinburgh, Scotland, agreed.
In addition to the growing resistance from the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called on NATO units to more activity, Britain sees priority in strengthening the Afghan government's authority and in intensifying development aid.
“In Afghanistan, a forward development is noticeable, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to allow residents to start a further development of the economy and security themselves," UK Defence Secretary Des Browne tells the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of Afghan insurgents has reached its highest level in five years, according to the American Army.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty percent.
NATO countries have deployed about 40000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have reached an absolute limit in terms of organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they are calling for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train the Afghan units.
"We will have to seriously reflect on the concrete goals for the next time and the way we can achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General, Jaap de Hoop, said the same today.
