Government debt will skyrocket to a trillion in 2009
Each Czech is subject to a national debt of 84000 kronor.
The total debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
The government had planned to default on 159.2 billion cons this year.
In early December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion thanks to the better development of state budget policy.
The Czech Republic's sovereign debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
Within the first nine months of this year, they increased by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance confirmed its information on the national debt from the beginning of October.
Each Czech accounts for a debt of 84000 crowns.
Over the past year, the state was in debt by more than 111 billion crowns.
“So far, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for the coming year, we will potentially not exceed the limit of one trillion crowns until 2009.
Next year, debt should move between 900 billion and a trillion crowns," David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told the server iHNed.cz.
Vladimír Pikora, an analyst at Next Finance, said: “We could get to exceed one trillion in the course of 2009.
When exactly, depends on the next budget that we do not yet know.
If it should become apparent that the situation on the political stage is changing, and politicians should be willing to save more, that could last until 2010.
But I don't expect such a change," he remarked.
Debt grows
The national debt stems from the debts of the state government and comes above all from the accumulation of deficits of the state budget.
The national debt is financed by Treasury notes, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, bonds of the European Investment Bank.
Domestic public debt has now risen to 719.4 billion kronor this year.
The state's foreign debt, meanwhile, rose by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable sovereign debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and fell by 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of the national debt rose to 6.5 years.
“The total debt increased by 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
It is interesting that the growth is mainly recorded in the case of bonds, where the increase is 20 percent.
It's bad that debt is rising, but on the other hand, this shows that you can do something even before the pension reform comes," Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
The financing strategy and the handling of the national debt for 2007 shows that the government had planned for this year to take in 159.2 billion crowns.
In early December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion crowns thanks to the better development of state budget policy.
This amount stems mainly from the state budget deficit, which will obviously reach 76 billion kronor this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
Furthermore, it is a maximum of planned funds for the consolidation agency of 13.3 billion kronor, a tens of billions of dollars in reserve to pay pensions, the financing of sovereign debt securities for 43 billion and installments for the bonds at the European Investment Bank of 1.8 billion.
For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of pupils complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Education several times, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Khartoum's Unity High School, was apprehended at her home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
“The children are proposing eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” reports headmaster Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Subsequently, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption “My name is Mohammed”.
The bear himself did not carry a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simply that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is seen as an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, declared that he knew her well, and she never had done anything to get too close to a religious belief, “I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name,” which, in his opinion, is only an “innocent mistake.”
An opinion that numerous students share of the teacher, who describe them as “very attentive to their students” and as a “person who never speaks about religion” in the class.
Keep in mind that the first name Mohammed is also the second most frequently given second name in the UK, for which 14 different spellings exist in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of reverence for the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
On Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province at the last negotiating meeting in Vienna.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion session Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their controversies over the future status of the separatist province.
“It is unfortunate that the parties could not reach an agreement on the status,” said the European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
With emphasis on the fact that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfil their commitments to preserve the peace, and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
“No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time,” he added, indicating that there are quite clear tensions.
End of the mediation on 10. December
The troika's mediators, which unites the European Union, the U.S. and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is 90% inhabited by Albanian-speaking people, could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko by the 10th. December submit their report to the UN Security Council.
The talks of Baden, near Vienna, formed the sixth and last negotiating session since the Troika received the order from the UN last August for a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation order to be placed on 10. December will end.
The Russians, who had already blocked the approval of Kosovo's independence at the Security Council, insist on a continuation of negotiations beyond that end date.
“Russia was and remains an advocate for a negotiated solution, a consensual solution,” said Botsane-Khartchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of being under the administration of the UN, the Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to announce them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favor.
Belgrade insists on stronger autonomy
“Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached,” announced the President of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, at the hotel in Baden, where these “negotiations of the last chance” have been conducted since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province shared his regrets.
However, he added that the Belgrade-proposed plan for autonomy “belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.”
Domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, was of the opinion that a compromise should always be sought, and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence by the province.
Belgrade thinks that it is particularly fearing a "domino effect" in a region that is still so weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
“For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible,” he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision be made solely and solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto power.
The Parliament of Kosovo will have the final say
"Only a decision from the ranks of the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
Fatmir Sejdiu replied to the journalists that “the parliament of Kosovo will have the final say on the status,” adding that any unilateral declaration of independence would be carried out by the Albanian-speaking people “in coordination” with the Western countries.
