A heavy souvenir
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, documenting the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen over a total length of 27 km, could not be viewed until now, unless with a “humanitarian” intention, i.e. individually and name-related, i.e. on the query of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, which were tasked with their administration, agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been in effect since yesterday.
Delicate information
The historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, “especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced labourers,” explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the intellectual disability of some deportation victims.
The inmates of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
“One must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents,” Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, explained in 2006.
