New fears over natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is simmering between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of hurting Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe.
Most of Russia's natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are routed through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is being watched very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for the natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two states in the last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states at talks," Ukraine's economy minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drove up prices dramatically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas deposits, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The consequence is that Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS 'must control foreign workers'
The Scottish State Health Service must improve controls on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, a member of the control body said. outside
The recommendation of main financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought into connection with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also raised concerns that the Scottish State Health Service did not have any precise ideas about the number of its foreign staff.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly on a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an SUV was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October, and was charged in connection with the suspected car bombing in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out checks in advance of employing foreign staff to ensure that they possess the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisations to operate in the United Kingdom.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have the responsibility to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main auditor's report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, these have not been routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative policies with high degree prior to employment, but added: "Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information about the number of foreign health service staff is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks in the run-up to hiring potential NHS staff.
"The report states that current pre-employment tests of the NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign staff, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was probably higher, also because the board members had problems identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation further found that established control procedures have been overwhelmingly adhered to by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
This includes passport, work permit and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for checks before employment begins for foreign staff at the NHS.
Secretary of Health Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices in updated guidance regarding the check-ups would be reflected in the run-up to the employment of all staff - including those from abroad - whose publication is planned next month.
