Is the credit crisis infecting America's credit card market?
When blood is in the water, it's just natural for dorsal fins to swirl around excitedly.
Now that America's real estate market is ailing, the predators have their sights set on the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs expect that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer loans.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are rises in both debiting and late-lending rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are not collectible or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 billion fee collection from its American consumer financing, partly because of the weakness of credit card takers.
It is too early to panic.
Losses and latencies are still low.
According to the rating agency Moody, the third-quarter default rate of 3,89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in the rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in American private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt case of bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large part of the credit card losses; the number of registrations (and thus default fees) would increase again, whether or not the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
The industry also reports solid payment rates showing how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the standstill in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, expects that the output volumes for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
Direct channels of infection between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: it is more likely that consumers will take credit card debt, now that home loans are drying up.
However, the card issuers look to the flow of money instead of capital values, which is why falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the creditworthiness of the borrower.
They can even be beneficial for the card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates drop when the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; as a result, the card debt becomes more important among the repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and completely re-evaluate the loans," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's main financial officer.
Even if a sudden underfunding crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are considerably more real.
If lower house prices and a credit mitigation push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
