Venus is the hell of the Earth's twin
Venus, despite its hostile atmosphere, is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected it's flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soup theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms in the ocean are said to have stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there's ever been life there, it must have been in the very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there should hardly be anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's devil twin, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early 1990s, no probe was on the road specifically to explore this planet.
The latest research, now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only highlights the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also show that the commonalities of our neighboring planet with Earth are greater than initially thought," the Esa said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud vortex at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the earthly winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, is almost as large.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, circles around the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much more slowly around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 days of earth.
Although Venus hardly resembles Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up the bulk of the atmosphere on Venus.
