Von Beust reaps criticism for Olympic cancellation
The mayor’s backing away from Hamburg’s bid for the Summer Olympics has met with severe criticism from politics and business.
Many want to keep fighting for the games on the water.
But von Beust calls for realism in assessing the opportunities.
The chief executive of the Hamburg Chamber of Commerce, Hans-Jörg Schmidt-Trenz, on Wednesday described a waiver as "not good for the business location."
No other project has recently developed such great motivational staff in the city as the Olympic idea.
“Without this goal, the sports-political momentum would not be able to be maintained to the same extent.”
Schmidt-Trenz called on the Senate not to bury the project, but to find a new long-term approach to it, "which assumes a changed timeline."
Mayor Ole von Beust remained on Wednesday with previous statements that the Olympic ambitions of Hamburg were unrealistic at least until 2028.
"It is not Hamburg that decides on an Olympic bid, but the German Olympic Sports Federation," von Beust told WELT ONLINE.
He referred to the decision of the Sportbund on an application by Munich for the 2018 Winter Games, which was expected for the beginning of December.
“This preference means for us that we will have no realistic chances in the period we have previously planned until 2028.”
Still, the dream isn't dreamed out for all time, von Beust said.
The Hamburg Sportbund (HSB) regretted the statements of Beusts.
This will give the impression that Hamburg will no longer apply for the Olympic Games in the next 25 years.
"It is too early to obstruct an opportunity by already burying the plans at this point," HSB President Günter Ploß said on Wednesday.
A waiver of the application was also contrary to the statement of the head of the Senate on the occasion of a reception to the General Assembly of the General German University Sports Association.
There, von Beust described Hamburg's application for the 2015 Universiade "not as a replacement" for the Olympic Games in Hamburg.
The University Sports Association had only last week nominated Hamburg as a candidate city.
