These are not Warhol's boxes
Those who associate the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, fabricated wooden boxes in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
The majority of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" listed there are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" stoked doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968 a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995 as a donation, are copies of the majority of the art market.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-and-white design of the cardboard boxes of the soap powder "Brillo."
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were (for cost reasons) not from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time were then authorized original Andy Warhol-Brillo boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm" rightly entered the art and auction history.
Some of them have raised more than $100 000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg produced.
By that point, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three from Swedish private ownership, two of whom were made in Stockholm in 1968: their pressed chipboards were first primed and sanded, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint with a paint roll was applied directly to the pressed chipboard without a primer - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve said, "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the "serious accusations" that are made in matters of soap powder boxes.
But since then, people have been shrouded in relentless silence.
Rebeling soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebels have given up who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila and called for the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not answer for bloodshed, leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and voter fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Government-aligned soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under the use of tear gas.
The roughly two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
Around half of them were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle with around 30 sympathizers.
The military policemen, who were supposed to guard him, had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula hotel and demanded the ouster of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces cordoned off the district around the noble hotel.
The president convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National security adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' actions.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the Scout Rangers' elite unit, said other Army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the president for Friday.
Your government has been overshadowed by allegations of corruption for months.
Manila’s financial district was already the main scene of the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo in 2003.
The uprising failed after barely 24 hours at the army's refusal to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes major shareholder at Versatel
United Internet has secured a more than 20 percent stake in telecoms company Versatel.
The average price per share is €14.46, the company announced on Wednesday evening.
It now holds 20.05 percent of the share capital.
A takeover had previously been speculated.
Keep the option to increase the share of Versatel still open.
The move aims to promote the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Previously, suspicions about an entry had already arisen on Wednesday, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf-based network operator by a further 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house considers the shares only a third party, it said in the financial market.
The previous day, United Internet had already invested almost 10 percent in the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth 106.4 million euros.
United Internet has bought 5.15 million shares of this for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have started discussions about marketing cooperations for DSL and mobile phone products.
"We are strengthening our partnership," a United Internet spokesman explained.
The two companies have established the joint venture MSP to acquire the competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to settle for a good ten percent stake in Freenet and make no use of their right to acquire another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet said on Thursday.
However, the two companies kept all options open, in particular to further increase the stake in Freenet AG, it said.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
The poker around Freenet, which has been going on for months and is difficult to see through, is part of the consolidation of the German telecoms market.
Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and full-connect customers at the end of the third quarter.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch held directly 6.01 percent of the Freenet shares so far.
It has now been agreed that Drillisch will contribute a further four percent.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent from investment firm Vatas had already been agreed in August.
